{
  "answer": "**Allama Iqbal's poetry in the Falsafa corpus (from *Bang-e-Dara*) uses \"shahīd\" (شاہد) once directly, in the sense of \"witness\" rather than \"martyr,\" and evokes martyrdom (\"shuhadā\") symbolically elsewhere.**[^1][^2][^3]\n\nIn \"Himalaya\" (*Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, ch. 25), a singing mountain stream is described in the Urdu as \"*Āina sa shahīd-e-qudrat ko dikhlaātī huī*\"—like a mirror displaying the \"witness of divine power/nature\" (*shahīd-e-qudrat*). The English translation renders the stanza as: \"A mirror to the face of Nature, it does seem, / Now striking, now avoiding rocks within the stream,\" capturing the stream's reflective role in revealing nature's divine testimony.[^1][^4]\n\nThe term \"martyrs\" (*shuhadā*) appears twice in translations, portraying their blood as regenerative:\n- In \"Dil se jo baat nikalti hai\" (*Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, ch. 4): \"The garden will be cleansed of thorn and weed; / The martyrs’ blood, a life-bestowing seed, / Is painting all the flowerbeds with red.\" Here, martyrs' sacrifice revives the \"garden\" of Islamic faith/nation amid decay.[^2]\n- In \"Huzoor Risalat Ma'ab Mein\" (*Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, ch. 11), a vial of blood represents \"Tripoli's martyrs,\" symbolizing the ummah's honor offered to the Prophet.[^3]\n\n**The corpus contains no explicit philosophical definition or prose discussion of \"shahīd\" by Iqbal** (only these poetic *Bang-e-Dara* sections). It lacks his major works like *The Reconstruction of Religious Thought in Islam*, where he explores related ideas of self-sacrifice, witnessing truth (*shahādat*), and khudī (selfhood) in Islamic revival. In Urdu poetic tradition, \"shahīd\" often blends witness/martyr, testifying to divine reality through life or death—Iqbal's usage aligns poetically but isn't analyzed here.[^5]",
